\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

\emph{Wireless Sensor Networks} (WSNs) are enabling a myriad of novel \emph{Information Technologies} and \emph{Communication Applications}.
Our future \emph{Smart Cities} and \emph{Internet of Things} will also rely on technologies being developed in the realm of WSNs.
It is now evident that planet Earth will soon be instrumented by billions or trillions of micro and nanosensors---hopefully biodegradable.
For such a large scale deployment, application designers must consider a large number of failures, which will cause the network's topology to change constantly.
Many applications will also require nodes to go mobile, either embedded in some ordinary device or specifically designed to move around, such as floating sensors on a lake.
This class of WSN applications calls for routing algorithms able to deal with dynamic topologies and their resulting overhead.

Many routing concepts for networks have been developed, mainly for \emph{Mobile Ad Hoc Networks} (MANETs) [].
Protocols for mobile networks must be self-organizing and self-configuring to deal efficiently with dynamic topologies.
However, most of these solutions relies in mechanisms that generate additional overhead to manage mobility.
As a result, few of them can go with the low-resource and high-noise world of WSNs.

Among the routing algorithms for MANETs, ant-based algorithms have been effective to deal with mobility-related overhead~[].
Based on the \emph{Ant Colony Optimization} (ACO) metaheuristic, such algorithms employ pheromone as a metric to define the quality of routes.
The goal of this method is to abstract routing operations into simpler operations of pheromone's deposit and evaporation.
Many approaches based on ACO have been specifically designed for WSNs, due to such simplicity~[].

In this paper, we explore ACO-based routing techniques to design a routing algorithm which aims at reducing the routing overhead in mobile WSN environments.
We describe \emph{Ant-based Dynamic Hop Optimization Protocol} (ADHOP), a self-organizing and self-configuring routing algorithm for mobile networks~[].
We compare it with the HOPNET, a routing protocol for MANETs that aims at handling mobility efficiently~[].
We show in such comparison how to encompass many optimization criteria under the pheromone concept, thus allowing for a slim, yet configurable, implementation of a routing algorithm.
We also compare ADHOP with the most significant related ones by means of a simulation performed with OMNeT++, using a high mobility scenario for IEEE 802.15.4 networks.
We show how such optimizations help to achieve better results in terms of data delivery ratio and routing overhead.
Besides corroborating our claims, this evaluation sets guidelines that can be used by other researches while designing WSN routing algorithms.

